Non in rayno, etc. “ That the Roman people were no long- er under the dominion of their kings‚ but in the enjoyment of liber- ty.'’ Walker objecta to this natural and obvious meaning of the text, and says that the idea intended to be conveyed is as follows: ‘⁶ That the Roman people‚ under the govemment of the kingS, did not exist as a people,'' i. e.‚ had no power or influence3 but that now, in a free state, and in the enjoyment of liberty, they did exist as a people, i. e., had influence and power. An ingenious hut very improbable explana- tion. The meaning of Livy’s words is simply thie, that the Romane, being now in a state of liberty, were resolved to maintain that liberty, and have no more lainga—Eam esse voluntatem omnium.
